WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Good morning. It is June 29, 2016. This is David Klein of the History Department at Virginia Tech,

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.000
and also working with the Southern oral history program at UNC in Chapel Hill.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.000
This morning we are recording for the Civil Rights History Project and we are in San Diego, California.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:36.000
This project is sponsored by the Library of Congress and also the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Behind the camera today we have John Bishop of Media Generation and UCLA.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:48.000
We are also joined behind the camera by Guha Shankar of the Library of Congress and Jessica Jawat of Pillars of the Community,

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
which is a local organization we will hear a little bit more about here in San Diego.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.000
So we are incredibly honored to be able to spend some time this morning with the Bird Alexander.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:03.000
This is the one time I will coach you at all in our entire conversation,

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
but if you could introduce yourself with a full sentence, I am, or my name is,

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.000
and your name and where and when you are born.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Oh, I'm a Bird Alexander and I was born in December 1946 in Berkeley, California.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:26.000
So, Bird, I would love to start with telling us a little bit about your family background

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.000
and how that may have influenced you as you grew up.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:37.000
My family background definitely influenced me and my brother and sister very, very much.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Not my great grandfather, my grandfather was a slave.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:55.000
And that seems hard to imagine if you try to do the math, but he was born in 1842 and he died in 1942.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:02.000
And the article that was written about him in an Omaha newspaper said,

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:06.000
wrote about his having been a slave and my father had known he had been a slave,

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:11.000
and also wrote about him having participated in the Pony Express.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:22.000
My father grew up on the between the Omaha Indian Reservation and Su City, Iowa.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:30.000
So, most of his life he identified as not a member of the tribe,

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:37.000
because he knew he wasn't a member of the tribe, but all of his friends were kids from the reservation

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
or the kids in Su City, Iowa, who were like the children of packing house workers.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.000
Because his mother would go there to work in the packing houses at that time.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
How did he come to be associated with the reservation?

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Because of his father. His father actually spoke, my grandfather spoke,

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Winnebago, Omaha, and Su.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:06.000
And according to my dad, Su and Omaha are closely related languages and Winnebago is more different.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And according to family lore, he got this job on the Pony Express,

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:17.000
which would not have lasted very long, because the Pony Express was only in existence for about a year and a half.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:23.000
But because he could speak the Indian languages and could go through some areas where other people couldn't go.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:32.000
And he did it on the condition that he would tell the white people nothing about what the Indians were doing.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
So, they ended up living there.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.000
But it was mostly my grandmother who was home.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:45.000
My grandfather did lots of different things.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.000
He was an itinerant musician, actually.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:55.000
And he played the Jews harp, and he traveled with the guy named Giles, who played the 12th string guitar.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:01.000
He also was a bootlegger for a period of time.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:06.000
He also wrestled cattle and sold cattle.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:13.000
So, he was not home very often, but he did manage to have 10 children.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:20.000
And my grandmother was little Scott Irish lady who ended up living mostly on the reservation.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Amazing family background.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
And so, and then you are your own father in his siblings.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
So, my father was born in the 18th century.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
My father was born in 1914.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:38.000
So, if you do the math, his father was pretty old when he was born.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
My father had nine siblings, five girls and five boys.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
And three of the girls died of different things.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:57.000
One of the flu, the flu pandemic, another of tuberculosis, and the third one in a fire.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
When they were home, because they were often home alone.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
When she was working in the packing houses in Susie, Iowa, and I think she was ironing or something.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.000
And there was a fire, and so she died in that.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.000
And did he stay your father in that area?

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Well, that's an interesting question, because no, in the end he came to California.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.000
But growing up, he, he, at one point we did an oral history with my dad.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
And at one point he said, home, what was home?

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.000
We were always staying with different people.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:36.000
So, if you think about it, his mother also died fairly early, because she had tuberculosis.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
She died when he was 15.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.000
But growing up, he was sometimes in Susie, Iowa, with his mother.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
He was sometimes on the reservation with his mother.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:51.000
At other times, he was with his brother, Earl Alexander.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:57.000
And at another time, he was in Flint, Michigan, with another brother, Mark Alexander,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.000
who worked in the automobile plants.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:03.000
And was very religious, and my father sort of ran away from there,

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
but he worked as a bell hop in Flint, Michigan.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:14.000
So, between the years of 10 and 15, he must have lived in 10 or 15 different places.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
And done, just as many jobs.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:23.000
There's one in particular that I would like you to tell you about when he was about 12.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:32.000
He decided to work, to ride the rails, and get work in the harvest in Minnesota.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And when we had the reunion for our family on the reservation,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
we could see that the rail lines go right through the reservation.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
It would have been easy for him to hop on.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.000
So, he did, a 12-year-old, 12-13-years-old.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
He goes to Minnesota, riding the rails.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:55.000
He gets off some place, and he asks around, does anybody need any help doing the harvest?

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
So, he finds this farmer, and the guy says, yeah, I need some help.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
And this is where I live, and come out at 6 o'clock or something like that, and I'll get you set up.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:11.000
And he gave my dad some money to buy some food, but he didn't give him any money to get out to the farm.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:15.000
The farm was about five miles out, or he didn't offer him a ride, I should say.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And my dad gets out there, and the farmer is doing chores, so my dad helps him do the chores with the different animals,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:28.000
the chickens, and milk, and all the cows, and everything.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:34.000
Then he goes into the bunk house, and the farmer's wife brings him food.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:42.000
He always talks about food, because that was really important, because he said he was hungry 99% of the time, so he says,

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:47.000
she brought me sandwiches, and some milk, and I thought, oh, this is cool.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:53.000
And the farmer offered to pay me 50 cents a day, and that's terrific.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:01.000
So, he notices that in the bunk house there's a bunch of all-grown men, and they're all white, of course.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:07.000
So, anyway, one of them comes up to him, and they say, so, what are you doing here?

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:15.000
Koon, or some kind of, you know, derogatory term, or really my dad would say he didn't know what that meant at that stage.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:17.000
And he says, well, I'm here to work the harvest.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
The guy says, really, you're here to work the harvest? He says, yeah.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:29.000
He says, what's he paying you? 50 cents a day, and the guy says, 50 cents a day, and you're doing chores on top of it?

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And he says, yeah, because he's so proud of himself.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
And the guy says to him, they're Scandinavian, by the way.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
My father say, they're Swedes, nor Weedgeans, and so forth.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:43.000
And the guy says, you can't work for 50 cents a day.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
You're a worker just like we are.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.000
You have to get a dollar a day, just like we do.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Then my dad says, oh, oh, this is terrific, you know, but he's kind of nervous because the guy was calling him a shine and a koon.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And all of these things.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So next morning at breakfast, my dad explains the breakfast sausage, biscuits, gravy, pancakes, bacon, eggs.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And he says in the middle of all of this feast, this guy stands up and tells the farmer, we understand you're hiring this boy for 50 cents a day.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
And the farmer says, that's right.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:27.000
And he says, no, you can't do that.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:31.000
Either you fire him or you give him a dollar a day.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And then the guy says, well, I don't know what to do.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:37.000
He says, no, actually, you give him a dollar a day or we strike.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And my dad's going, strike, he's going to strike.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.000
I barely finished my breakfast because he knew what a strike was.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:52.000
He had lived in Su City, Iowa with his mother in the late teens and in the early 20s.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
And there were strikes at the packing house.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And he would describe all of the people who were on strike.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And it was amazing because he listed Mexicans, Syrians, and Poles and Russians, as well as a few black folks and a few Indians.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:15.000
And at that time, there was a real campaign of terror against the strikers.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:22.000
So for example, my dad would never sit at night in front of a window that was not covered.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
Ku Klux Klan would march down the street.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
And he felt they targeted his mom, but then he's because she had these black kids.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
But then he said, no, they targeted everybody.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And they would throw rocks in the windows and terrorized folks.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
So back to the breakfast.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
He says, strike, we can't go strike.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
I have barely finished my breakfast.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
And the guy says, nope, we're going to do this.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:50.000
So the owner says, well, okay.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.000
But he's got to carry his weight.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
So my dad starts working with him.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
And he's running as fast as he can.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
And it was what they called shocking grain.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
So the grain would be cut.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:06.000
And then they would pick it up and tie it up and pile it in piles.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.000
So he was running.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:12.000
So the guy says to him, what's you doing running like that?

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
You're not supposed to be setting the pace.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:16.000
You see him?

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:21.000
You go as fast as he goes and you don't go any faster.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
He says, okay, I'm just trying to prove.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:28.000
Excuse me.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:31.000
I'm just trying to prove that I can keep up my,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:32.000
keep up with everybody else.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
So the long story short, he works there for about a month.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
He makes about $30.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:39.000
And he's so happy.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
He's getting ready to go home.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And the guy says, okay.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:46.000
So now you understand where the industrial workers of the world

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
and you need to join.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
And so you can get a membership for $0.10 a month.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And here's your card.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
So my dad gave the guy $30.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:01.000
And he had a little red card for being a member of the I.W.W.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:05.000
And at that time, I guess he might have been the youngest one.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.000
And also he was a black kid up in the Midwest.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
And it was pretty, it was a pretty special designation.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
What an amazing, amazing story.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
So that's just one story.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.000
We've just started.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
I can't wait for the rest of this.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:22.000
Fantastic.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.000
Yes, thank you.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:28.000
I think that story is very important because he had,

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
although his mother was white, he was always around the Native Americans

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
and the African Americans who were living in Su City.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
And he said he didn't know very many white people.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:44.000
And yet he had this experience where these grown white guys stood up for his rights.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:51.000
He was a little scared because they were known for, like, they would burn somebody's field down.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
They were anarchists, I guess, in part.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.000
And he was frightened by the whole thing.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And he was also confused.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
And he spoke up when he spoke up to the guy.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.000
He says, you guys are calling me shine and cool and all those.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
That makes me feel kind of funny.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
I would prefer you just call me by my name.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.000
And that was kind of interesting.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:18.000
And most of them did, but they would forget and call him those names anyway.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:26.000
But I think that was a very formative moment for him, as well as having experienced as a child,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:30.000
his mother's work in the packing house and the strikes there,

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
which were very multiracial, multiethnic.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
Now did he tell you these stories when you were growing up?

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
Did you know these stories of the unions?

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
I only knew some of these stories.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:49.000
I didn't really get any of the details until we did oral history on him in 1975.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:54.000
I knew about the Indians because they showed up in Los Angeles once.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:59.000
The whole family didn't tell anybody and they just arrived.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:05.000
And we took care of them, half of them, half my cousins had TB.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And they were put in sanitariums.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:15.000
But we had other cousins who would stay at different brothers' houses in LA.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.000
So I knew about that.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
And we would do stuff like the squad dance and things like that.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
And we would eat fried bread when they came.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:24.000
Yeah.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
So you had some awareness of this.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
Oh yeah, I had awareness of it.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
Yeah, I did.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:34.000
So how about, so you said your father eventually ended up in California,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
but can you tell us a bit about your mother?

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
Okay.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
Can I tell you a little more about my grandmother?

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:41.000
Absolutely.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:45.000
So my father only went to about the fifth grade.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:49.000
And my grandmother was a real fighter.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:54.000
And this is another part of making my dad who he was.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:59.000
For example, he loved school.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
He even talked about how he liked his teachers.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
This is when he would have been in Su City.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
And they had a substitute one day.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:11.000
And the substitute was mean.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
And she was hitting the kids on their fingers with a ruler.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
So he got hit once.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
And then I don't know what he did.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
He doesn't even remember what he did.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.000
And he said to himself,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.000
she's not going to hit me no more.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:31.000
And he snatched the ruler out of her hand,

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
broke it in half, and threw it out the window.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:39.000
Well, this substitute teacher kind of had a fit after that happened very upset

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.000
and was taking him out of school.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:45.000
He went home and told his mother what happened.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:50.000
His mother came back and you know they had ink wells at that time.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:55.000
And she just picked up the ink well, she told off this woman

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:00.000
for treating the children badly and she threw the ink at this teacher.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:03.000
And then they marched away.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:08.000
Another time they were trying to get enrolled in school and they didn't have shoes.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
And they said, you can't have shoes.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
So the mother said, well, let's just go.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:13.000
They left.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
And he needed to find work anywhere and not anyway.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
And that's when his education stopped.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:24.000
So imagine, sushi to the Iowa and you don't have shoes.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:28.000
So my mother's family,

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:34.000
that's another story.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:39.000
My grandmother comes from Vilna,

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.000
which is Lithuania.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:45.000
We grew up understanding that it was sometimes Russian,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:46.000
it was sometimes Poland.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:49.000
And they were Jewish.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:56.000
And they immigrated, well, the family was very revolutionary.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
They were anti-zar.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
And they,

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:05.000
that the family back there was Orthodox Jew,

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
the family that she grew up in.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:13.000
But she and almost all of her siblings eventually came to the United States

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:17.000
after 1905 revolution.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:24.000
And my grandfather was Russian and I don't know where he was from.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.000
But he Russian Jew.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:33.000
But he was a very angry, bitter, mean man.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
He had a shoe repair store in St. Louis.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:42.000
And when my mother later met my father in California,

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
he disowned her, my mother, because my father was black.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
Well, we said, need grow at that time.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:18:00.000
And so my grandmother decided to leave him because she was not going to disown her daughter.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Yeah.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.000
And this whole, all of her siblings,

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:08.000
they did not practice Judaism as a religion really,

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
but they spoke Yiddish.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
That was their main language.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
They were culturally Jewish.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:22.000
And they were all very, very progressive and involved in the movement in some way or another.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.000
My grandmother worked in the garment industry.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.000
My grandmother was very upset with the Jewish religion,

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
because for example, the boys could go to school and she couldn't.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
So my grandmother was essentially illiterate.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
She could read a little bit of Yiddish

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:43.000
and she could add, and very little bit of English, her whole life.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:47.000
But they were always very, very progressive.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:58.000
And my parents met because at some young communist league party in Los Angeles.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.000
I have a lot of stories about how my father decided to become a communist.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
I don't know if you have time for them.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
How about one or two?

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
One or two.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:17.000
So my father, when he was maybe 12, did a short job in the packing house,

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:24.000
which was, and just involved opening the door so somebody else carrying a big hunk of meat could get through.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:32.000
And he worked as a shoe shine boy at different places for a lot of his life at that age.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:37.000
And as a shoe shine boy, somebody came by, some young woman, he said,

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:43.000
came by God of shoe shine, and then left him a copy of the Communist Manifesto.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.000
So he's trying to read the Communist Manifesto, because he's kind of impressed.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:52.000
Nobody ever gave him a book before or anything, but he didn't have the skills to do it.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:56.000
So he asked his boss, and his boss says, that's terrible.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:57.000
That's terrible stuff.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:59.000
He says, oh, okay, and he throws it away.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:03.000
And then when his boss is not there, he picks it up again.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:08.000
And he had a very good relationship with the banker in town,

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:14.000
and even figured out how to borrow $50 from the banker for his brother to buy a truck.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:17.000
He had this nice relationship, so he figured the banker could help him.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:23.000
So he shows the banker, his copy of the Communist Manifesto, and the banker says,

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.000
that's just terrible, revolutionary crap, terrible, terrible.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.000
So my father throws it away again.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:32.000
But then he starts thinking, well, this is kind of an interesting book.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.000
And he keeps trying, but he really can't read it.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:40.000
And at some point, this young woman comes back, and she says, how are you doing with the book?

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:43.000
And he says, actually, I can't read it.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:44.000
I can't read well enough.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:47.000
I'd be happy to talk to you about it, but I can't read.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:54.000
And then he was invited to a party, and was rather amazed, you know,

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:57.000
that the party was all white people.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:02.000
And he mentioned Jews and Russians and Scandinavians and things like that at the party.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:06.000
But everybody was nice to him and inclusive, and they started,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:11.000
when they heard his stories, they could not believe his background,

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
and that they were very friendly.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:16.000
And that's how he started to get involved.

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.000
And then later on, working in the packing house,

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:25.000
because he then got real job in the packing house when he was 16 or 17.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:28.000
And I guess he was talking to these folks at the time,

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:31.000
and talking to the workers in the packing houses,

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.000
and the packing houses actually haven't changed that much.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:37.000
He said, we would be in a foot of manure, and there would be blood everywhere,

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:41.000
and your hands would be very slippery, and it was extremely dangerous,

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:45.000
and there were always people at the doors ready to take your place,

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:48.000
and they were always training new people.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:53.000
And they worked 10 to 13 hour days,

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:56.000
and they had 20 minutes for a lunch break.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:02.000
And he talked about how they would drink blood just to keep themselves going.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:07.000
Some positions were not on a conveyor belt, but other positions were.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:17.000
And they would start at 250, not goats, sheep going by,

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:20.000
in the morning, and then they would gradually increase it,

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:23.000
and sometimes it got up to 350.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:27.000
And so he talked to the guys and said, well, what are we going to do about this?

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:31.000
Because it's so dangerous when it gets up, because people would cut themselves,

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:33.000
very serious, no breaks.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:35.000
And he says, what are we going to do?

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:40.000
And somebody said, well, if they go over at 350, let's strike.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:44.000
My dad said, okay, maybe he was the guy who said, let's strike.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:48.000
Anyway, of course, they went over 350.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:52.000
My dad said, hold the line, and they all walked out.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
So it was a wildcat strike.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:59.000
He got fired and blacklisted, and everybody else went back to work.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:03.000
But what's really interesting about that story is, if you read the book, fast food nation,

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.000
very little has changed.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:08.000
In fact, I mean, these packing houses are larger,

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:12.000
but the jobs are very close to being as dangerous.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:17.000
And they talk about the speed of the line, exactly the same stuff,

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:20.000
mostly immigrant workers.

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:23.000
And this was in Los Angeles, right?

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:28.000
The packing house was in Sus City, and in Omaha.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:31.000
And then the depression was very, very difficult.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:38.000
And after he got blacklisted, though, that's when he came to California.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:45.000
So perhaps talking about California and how your parents met and then your own childhood.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:50.000
Okay, so my parents met in the Young Communist League movement as well.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.000
And how old were they?

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:56.000
They were probably in their young 20s, and it was interracial couples.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:59.000
It was illegal at that time.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:03.000
So they had a common law marriage.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:09.000
My mother was kind of the person who kept my dad going, but she wasn't the person with the big stories

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:12.000
who gave the speeches and things like that.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:20.000
He worked in California all up and down the Central Valley with cotton-conpress workers organizing for the CIO.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:29.000
And he also worked with the ILWU organizing African-American workers.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:37.000
And I think especially interesting for this project was that in the late 40s and early 50s,

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:42.000
he was the director of the Civil Rights Congress in Oakland, California.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:50.000
And they worked on police brutality, housing rights.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:55.000
They were attacked by the Oakland Tribune, Nolan newspapers.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:59.000
And one thing I talked about, lynching is genocide.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:04.000
This is a very important and little known organization.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
Yes.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:13.000
And what I think what's really important is, yes, he did identify as a communist.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:22.000
But what the communists did was organize for people's rights, for decent wages, for a place to live,

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:28.000
against police brutality, really basic people's rights.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:33.000
They weren't armed and going out to shoot people to have a revolution.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:38.000
It was their idea was, let's help the people where we are now.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:43.000
And that's part of the organizing effort for the Congress of Industrial Organizations to,

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:51.000
the CIO, was to be much more inclusive in terms of who was able to, who was unionized in an official way.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:53.000
Yeah.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:59.000
And your parents had met as young communists as your mother, retained those politics as well.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.000
She did. They didn't retain those politics.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:08.000
I mean, they both quit probably in the very early 60s,

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:11.000
because lots of different issues that were going on.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:17.000
She did a lot of support stuff like, I remember as a child going door to door selling the people's world.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:25.000
And going to a few demonstrations like about the Brosenbergs, it seems to, I would have been pretty small.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:36.000
And my dad, even after he stopped working as an organizer for unions and became a shoe repairman,

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:41.000
he would go hang out at the laborers' local in Los Angeles,

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:50.000
which was kind of a sold out local and then organized the workers to sort of struggle within the union for to change.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:54.000
And he organized an organization called the Laborers' Fraternal Order.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:57.000
And they had a logo, you know, they would have, they had these buttons,

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:02.000
and they had a logo with a brown arm, a white arm, and a black arm.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:07.000
In fact, I have a brochure that shows you that.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:10.000
Again, that was called the Laborers' Fraternal Organization.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:13.000
Laborers' Fraternal Order, I think.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:16.000
And it was a support group they had out.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:22.000
They had a baseball team, you know, it was community, a little bit like pillars of the community.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:29.000
So can you tell us a little bit about your own, obviously just a very typical childhood.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:30.000
Yeah.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.000
Tell us a little bit about your childhood.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:34.000
Yeah.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:38.000
Well, my childhood was kind of interesting because I was the youngest.

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:43.000
And so my brother and sister remember suffering more than I did.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:51.000
Some of my earliest memories when my father went underground,

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:55.000
he kind of, he disappeared during the McCarthy era.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:58.000
And of course, I didn't really know what that was about.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:04.000
But we lived with my uncle Mark in Paris, California, P-E-R-R-I-S,

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:10.000
which one was one of the few places where black people could buy land in the 30s and the 40s.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:11.000
Where about says that?

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:14.000
It's off 15.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:17.000
Where's it off the 163?

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.000
Not too far from Riverside.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:20.000
Okay.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:24.000
South West of Riverside.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:30.000
So it's a dry, rocky area.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:31.000
Very hard.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:34.000
You wouldn't make a living off the farm.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:42.000
And so we were country kids, and we looked like it in a couple of photographs that we have.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:46.000
My brother at the age of 12 dug a well.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:47.000
This will give you an idea.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:48.000
He dug the well.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:53.000
He still had the chair before he died to show us what he had done.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:56.000
And everybody in that family worked very hard.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
Like I was like the assistant.

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.000
So birdie, go get this, birdie, go get that.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:05.000
You know, I was that person because he needed somebody.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:07.000
My sister worked very hard.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:10.000
And they were very frugal.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:12.000
The family was very frugal.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:15.000
I didn't feel like I suffered at all.

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:18.000
I felt, I thought everything was fine.

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:22.000
But once a week we would go to the grocery store with my uncle's truck

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:25.000
and take everything that they were throwing away.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.000
And we would bring that food back to our little farm.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
It was a five acre farm.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:35.000
To our little farm and sort through it and decide what we could keep to eat and what we'd go to the pigs.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:38.000
And we kind of did that, you know.

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:43.000
My uncle also worked as a custodian on Camp Pendleton, and he got fired.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:46.000
And he got fired because he was my father's brother.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:47.000
Period.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:51.000
This particular uncle was not political.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:54.000
And they were very religious.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:30:01.000
One of these sort of, it was the church of God in Christ.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:03.000
What do they call it?

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:08.000
They would sing, they would find the holy ghost.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:12.000
They would kind of light a half fits and stuff and speak in tongues and everything.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.000
Patek Ostle.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:15.000
I don't know.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:16.000
I don't know technically.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.000
There's a couple of words for them.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:23.000
Anyhow, they had this rusty, dusty little church with benches,

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:26.000
that do splinters and everything.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:29.000
And according to my brother and sister, we went like three times a week.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:32.000
Not just on Sunday, but during the week.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:39.000
I don't remember so much about it, except I did have nightmares for about three years of a devil chasing me.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:45.000
What else did I want to tell you about this period?

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:46.000
Oh, yes.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:47.000
We were followed.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:51.000
My brother, my sister and my uncle,

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:56.000
would be often followed when we were driving around because the FBI would be in some white,

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:59.000
not white, black, forward or Chevrolet.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:03.000
And they would follow my uncle like we were doing anything.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:08.000
And so my uncle decided one day, he wasn't political, but still he wanted to mess with these guys.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:16.000
So he went and parked in a cold sat, it's country, but it was like a dead end under a tree.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
And then it just stayed there.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:23.000
So they had to be in the sun, and this would be 100 degrees.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:26.000
In Paris, California, then sometimes you go out and say,

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:29.000
what do you guys follow us around for?

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:36.000
So I remember that, and then we did eventually move, we moved to Venice Beach, actually,

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:40.000
because my grandmother lived near.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:44.000
And so my mother took us off the farm and we moved to Venice Beach.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:47.000
And that was kind of a nice period.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:50.000
It was the one time I saw my grandfather, one time.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:54.000
I only saw him one time because my uncle came to town.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:57.000
He called his father and he said, if you want to see me,

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:00.000
you have to see Ette also in the kids.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:02.000
And so they came.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:03.000
He came.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:06.000
And that was the only time that I saw him.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:10.000
But I also knew that I was missing my father so much, I decided to run away.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:13.000
I was like five or four.

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:19.000
And I fill up a pillow with all of my necessities, and my mom said, okay,

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:20.000
and then I ran away.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
I maybe made a block and a half.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:26.000
I have no, I don't remember how it ended, but I didn't get very far.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:34.000
So as I was growing up, eventually my father had a heart attack.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:37.000
And so he came and lived with the family.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:42.000
And he learned how to be a shoe repairman just by a print-tossing himself for free

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:46.000
with a shoe repair fellow who taught him the trade.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:48.000
And we got a little shop.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:52.000
And we all worked in that shop, all five of us.

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:54.000
And of course I was still kind of young.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:57.000
So sometimes I would be in the back reading my books, you know.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:00.000
And then sometimes I'd be on the cash register.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:05.000
And eventually by the time I got to high school, I knew how to do some repair.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:11.000
I could put the heels on, and I could sand them on the machines, and do a lot of that.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:14.000
So we spent a lot of time there.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.000
And where was the shoe shop?

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:23.000
Well, the first one, well, we had one on Dinker Street, but then we had one on 39th and Western, on Western.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:27.000
And then the last one was a cross street from the City Hall.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:33.000
And one day, I don't remember the year.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:42.000
My father's name appeared in the Los Angeles Times because he was being called before Huac, House of Un-American Activities Committee.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:49.000
And a few months later that shoe repair shop got shot into during the night.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:54.000
And the other thing that happened is we had been going to this camp called Any Town.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.000
And it was very nice camp.

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:02.000
It was organized by the National Conference of Christians and Jews in CCJ.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:06.000
And my sister, it was very nice.

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:09.000
My sister was elected the mayor of Any Town.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
And she was very proud of that.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.000
And there was kids from all different high schools.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:15.000
So it was a real mixture of people.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:22.000
And the director of that program called her in, and she asked her, is that your dad?

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:23.000
My sister said, yes.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:28.000
She said, you can't be the mayor of this organization anymore.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:31.000
So that was devastating for my sister.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:34.000
And my sister remembers everything as we were poor.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:36.000
We didn't have stuff.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:43.000
I had to, she had to run the shoe shop for a whole week once when my parents were ill.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:46.000
And she, you know, she was like in the 11th grade or something.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:48.000
And she held down the entire fort.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:52.000
But she felt she suffered a lot behind that.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:35:00.000
So also in these years, I started to demonstrate in the civil rights demonstrations.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:06.000
But before we get to those demonstrations, like probably everybody you're interviewing, who's my age,

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:14.000
the first conversation that my father officially had with me about politics was when Emmett Till was murdered.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.000
Because we saw the jet man.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:18.000
He showed me, he says, birdie, that was my nickname.

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:22.000
You have to understand what this whole country is like.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:28.000
And we had the jet magazine and the pictures and everything.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:33.000
That's my first political conversation that I remember ever having.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:38.000
Do you remember your reaction to seeing the pictures or to your father talking to him?

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:39.000
I was horrified.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:43.000
He said, you know, things are not the way you may think they are.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:47.000
And I want you to know this is something that has just happened.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:49.000
I was just absolutely horrified.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:56.000
I knew I felt different because I,

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.000
we moved around a lot.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:03.000
And sometimes when I was quite young, I was in schools with all white kids.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.000
And I felt somehow different.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:09.000
I ended up making good friends with the other black girl and the third grade.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.000
And she was also tall because that made it.

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:15.000
I was very tall for my age.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:19.000
But I was not aware of that kind of violence.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:22.000
And my father is another thing he had done.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:27.000
He of course was very aware when he was 13 or 14,

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:33.000
a friend of his, a good friend of his brother was murdered by the police in custody.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.000
Beat up and murdered.

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:38.000
And nobody wanted to do anything about this.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:44.000
And my father collected money for the funeral, tried to get up church.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:49.000
The churches were intimidated and would not allow the funeral to be at the church.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.000
And they managed to do it.

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:53.000
I don't remember where.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:56.000
And something he pointed out, he said, you know, the prostitutes were really good.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:58.000
They really contributed a lot of money.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:01.000
Because they understood what that kind of hardship was.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:04.000
And that kind of brutality.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:07.000
So that's when I started hearing some of those stories from my dad.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:13.000
But that was the first conversation in it too.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:16.000
Something else that affected our childhood a lot was my,

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
our parents' interracial marriage.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:22.000
Because that was very unusual.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:26.000
And people would stare at us and then we would smile back and stuff.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.000
But we were very aware of that.

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:31.000
And my brother actually looks kind of like just a Jewish guy.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:36.000
And he would get into fights with people saying, no, I'm Negro.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:39.000
He would actually get into fist fights with them.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:42.000
I don't know if these were black or white kids.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:49.000
My father said that his mother always told them, your Negro, don't let anybody tell you that you're anything else.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:53.000
And that's pretty much what my father told us as well.

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:56.000
Do you have a single memory of that?

00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:59.000
That was just recurring theme.

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:04.000
And it's particularly interesting because I'm the darkest of the siblings.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:07.000
So my sister could conceivably pass.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:11.000
And my brother very easily would pass.

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:16.000
I mean, he would fight not to pass as white.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:19.000
So that was very important.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:23.000
And then I went to a lot of different schools.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:28.000
But then I started going to Burrindo, Jr. High School and Burrindo, Jr. High.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:31.000
And then to Los Angeles High.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:36.000
And our neighborhood, we eventually moved to an area of Los Angeles,

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
which is like Adams and Vermont.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:43.000
And it had been primarily African-American neighborhood.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:50.000
But it rapidly changed into an immigrant neighborhood, mostly Central Americans.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
So I learned Spanish.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:39:01.000
So when I took Spanish in school, I talked to my neighbors and made friends with them.

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:07.000
And at LA High, I was in very, very mixed classes.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:12.000
There were a lot of Jewish kids coming from, you know, like the Fairfax area.

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:17.000
There were a lot of Japanese kids, some of whom had been born in the internment camps.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:22.000
And there were a lot of African-American kids.

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:25.000
And we got along pretty well.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:29.000
I mean, there would be a fight in that school once every couple of months.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.000
I don't like you see today.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.000
But of course, we were very tracked.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:42.000
And in Jr. High and part of high school, that's when I started to do dancing.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:52.000
And it was through the dancing that I met some wonderful people who also were very involved in folk music.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:40:01.000
And I just was kind of like a weirdo, you know, because I liked this old-time folk music and all of this stuff.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:05.000
My brothers and sister, they were kind of like listening to Motown.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:07.000
But I was doing my own thing.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:11.000
And I eventually learned to play the guitar and the banjo.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:13.000
And I liked different kinds of music.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:21.000
And I'm so happy to realize that my, I had an uncle Earl, who was a fiddle learned, played old-time music way back.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:27.000
In the early 1900s, he probably had a better ear than I had.

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:32.000
So what year did you graduate high school?

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:40.000
So I graduated, so I was involved in some of the demonstrations in Los Angeles at Woolworth and some of those kinds of things.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:46.000
And I decided I wanted to go to Berkeley and I graduated in 1964.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:50.000
So I arrived in Berkeley in the fall of 1964.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:41:00.000
Can I back you up just a little bit then to your early high school and you and your family's reaction to what we talked about Emmett Till.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:08.000
But back in 1955 in Montgomery or in, you know, 60 when the sit-in movement really starts to go throughout the South.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:12.000
Were you tracking that in Los Angeles? Were you getting news?

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:18.000
You know, basically we were constantly looking at all of this happening on the news.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:30.000
But that's the extent of it. You know, we were just very excited about it all and watching it on the news and seeing how all of this was progressing.

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:34.000
Okay. Okay, so sorry dinner. But so.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
Right. So 64 Berkeley.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:48.000
Because I had seen that there had been demonstrations at the Sheraton Palace to I think it was to integrate the staff there.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:53.000
And all kinds of things had been happening at Berkeley.

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:57.000
So I figured that was the place to go. And I managed to get in.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:02.000
They accepted me late because my grades weren't as good as there were supposed to be.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:08.000
And but they got good enough because they saw my senior grades. And I went to Berkeley.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:16.000
So when I had got accepted, all of all of the like dorms and the coops and all of that, they were full.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:24.000
So my dad drove up with me and introduced me to different people that he knew from the movement in Berkeley.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:36.000
And the first student at Berkeley to really befriend me and help me was Bettina Aptecker.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:46.000
And she was like maybe she was a junior, maybe she was a sophomore. But she invited me to her house and she introduced me to a couple of people.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:56.000
And her father of course is like a renowned communist scholar, member of the Communist Party back then, and did a lot of African American history work.

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:02.000
And I had heard of him and I kind of knew that you know these were established people.

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:14.000
But anyway, she was very friendly. She had me over for dinner and helped me plan my classes and who the TAs were and what I should do.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:24.000
And that made all the difference in the world. I think if you were walking into that school and you didn't know anybody or you didn't have a group to associate with, you would really be lost.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:29.000
And so Bettina got me started and I met a lot of very interesting people.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:32.000
And did you just happen to meet her or was that through your father's connect?

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:39.000
No, somehow it wasn't just happened. No, it was through my father's connections. Although he didn't introduce me to her directly.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:50.000
He introduced me to his friends which were people like Jessica Mittford and I don't know, Roscoe Proctor and a lot of activists from the Bay Area at that time.

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:53.000
Okay, so you really followed through your father's trust?

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:57.000
It was through my parents.

00:43:57.000 --> 00:44:06.000
So I met people who were in the Du Bois Club and also in the Communist Party at that time at UC Berkeley.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:11.000
So what happens at UC Berkeley in the fall of 1964 is the free speech movement.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:24.000
And the free speech movement is largely because the students at Berkeley were mobilizing in support of the Civil Rights movement in Oakland and San Francisco at the time.

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:30.000
And some of the people I met actually had been freedom writers this summer previous.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:43.000
And so when they tried to take down our tables and violate our right to free speech, we had a pretty massive movement and I got arrested in Sproul Hall.

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:52.000
And I was 17 at the time but I told him I was 18 so that I wouldn't go off all by myself to juvenile hall or something.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:58.000
I just gave him a different year and my parents wouldn't have to come up to the Bay Area.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:05.000
So I participated in that and that was very exciting moment.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:15.000
Then the next major thing that happened at Berkeley as I decided I wanted to study abroad in Spain in 1966 and 1967.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:20.000
Of course during this period we were demonstrating against the war in Vietnam.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:30.000
We were demonstrating for civil rights. Very, very active. It was a very, very, very active period.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:40.000
So I decided I wanted to study in Spain. I was a Spanish major by the way which was rather an odd thing to be but it was because of where I grew up.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:49.000
Well through the eyes of 17 year old I was ready for all of this. In many ways this is why I went to Berkeley.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:59.000
I was very excited about the demonstrations. I was always out there passing out leaflets as a member of the WWE Be Du Bois Club.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:06.000
It was pretty early in the semester that the free speech movement started well.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:13.000
It got started because it got started really quick. All it took was them to try to stop setting up the tables.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:18.000
I don't know what they wanted to do that for because we really organized behind it.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:25.000
And so of course Mario Savio was one of the key figures and we had rallies just about every day.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:37.000
Bettina Abtecker also spoke. I spoke once as well and started to get my feet wet a little bit with giving speeches and things like that.

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:46.000
And it was mainly the free speech movement in 1966. Not in 1966, in 1964 of course.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:54.000
That I remember. And exactly what happened between then and going to Spain I actually can't remember.

00:46:54.000 --> 00:47:01.000
All of the things that we were involved in but constantly involved. Constantly doing things.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:11.000
So when I interviewed to go to Spain they said well you got arrested in the free speech movement and you're going to a country that is a dictatorship.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:25.000
And I said well my purpose is to go study. So I go. And I get to Spain and to Madrid and it truly was a repressive regime.

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:32.000
You saw there are so many different kinds of police and there were these police that you called the grises because they were gray.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:36.000
And they would be standing on corners with some machine guns.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:43.000
You didn't easily meet other political people.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:55.000
We studied in what you call the facultad de letras, de filosofía.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:59.000
Dendered the Berkeley folks, warn you at all, like be cool.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:04.000
No they asked the question but I answered it to their satisfaction.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:16.000
So I would find out there was a demonstration a day later because the way the Spanish students organized things as they would throw out leaflets, the demonstration would happen and it would be over.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:24.000
Because it's not something that you you know you wait at the front of the campus and you pass out leaflets. That was not happening.

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:31.000
And mostly they were demonstrating against the Franco, the Franco regime and against the dictatorship.

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:41.000
And I did eventually meet some Spaniards who were progressive and involved in some of this and I said, well what should I do?

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:49.000
And they said well you should work with the American students because we work with the Spanish ones. So what do we do? We set up a table.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:54.000
We get a table, we put it up in the facultad de filosofía, de letras.

00:48:54.000 --> 00:49:02.000
And we took signatures of people who were opposed to the war in Vietnam because we figured we better not touch Franco Spain.

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:11.000
And I do believe that the purpose of collecting those signatures was to take them to the embassy and that was naive on our part.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:20.000
But what was very interesting was with our little table there and I don't even remember how many days we were there, the press came.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:27.000
Different people from the press and they say let us know if you ever get ready to do anything because they wanted to be present.

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:30.000
We say okay fine, well let you know.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:45.000
So I was really mostly depressed most of the time that I was in Spain. I didn't find a boyfriend and I unfortunately didn't study flamenco guitar or whatever.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:54.000
But eventually by the spring I had quite a few progressive friends, well they were considered revolutionary at that time.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:57.000
And that was getting to be more and more fun.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:06.000
So they were planning to have big demonstrations against the war in Vietnam on April 28th, 1967.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:09.000
And they asked me if I would give a speech.

00:50:09.000 --> 00:50:14.000
And I said I don't know, maybe I'll write a letter and you can read the letter.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:19.000
So the director of our program was Carlos Blanco Aguinaga.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:29.000
And he actually left Spain in the 30s as a child of Spaniards when the war was lost.

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:39.000
And he lived in refugee camps in southern Spain and he became a very prestigious professor in the University of California system.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:49.000
And Spain didn't even want to accept him as the director of our study abroad program, but you see actually insisted that he be accepted.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:51:03.000
So he actually, when he found out that I was some kind of an activist because I avoided all authority, I didn't go anywhere near him, he called me into his office like in October.

00:51:03.000 --> 00:51:14.000
And he says, Roberta, Ronald Reagan is coming to town and you could go to the airport and he starts driving, driving me a diagram of the airport.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:19.000
And he says and you can put sign up under your, you can put a sign under your coat.

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:25.000
And then when he gets there, you can open up your sign against the war in Vietnam and against Ronald Reagan.

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:34.000
I go, man, this guy's crazy. Fortunately Ronald Reagan didn't come because I think I might have gotten home sooner.

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:44.000
If he had actually come. But anyway, Carlos Blanco had a separate meeting with the American embassy because they didn't meet with him with the rest of the directors.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:51.000
They met with him separately. And they basically told the directors of the programs, we can't protect your kids if they get involved in these demonstrations.

00:51:51.000 --> 00:52:00.000
So you need to tell them to stay out of the demonstrations. So Blanco has this meeting with all of us and he tells us the same thing.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:08.000
And then afterwards, I tell him, well, you know, they've asked me to give a speech. And he says, Roberta, I know you'll do the right thing.

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:11.000
He didn't tell me, don't give the speech.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:24.000
So the day of this event, I go and they've taken over a whole building and they have a sign like from the fifth floor to the second floor, you know, Yankee's for the other Vietnam.

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:31.000
My juice is 1967 in Europe. People were burning little American flags and things like that.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:40.000
So I go into the room where it's supposed to happen. The room is packed. The sound system doesn't work, but they say, don't worry, they'll get quiet.

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:49.000
There's a person before me. Nobody was listening to everybody. It was just chaos. And the reporters were asking me, what are they saying?

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:55.000
This is Spanish. You know, and the international reporters are asking me to translate for them.

00:52:55.000 --> 00:53:06.000
So it's my turn to speak. I wish I had saved that speech. But as soon as I get up there, I get this standing ovation and then I make my points.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:18.000
Oh, they got quiet, of course. And I get all of these, all of these plots and everything's just great. I'm so popular because I'm just like revolutionary student from the United States.

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:29.000
And then it's over. And like five students come up to me and they say, okay, now we have to run out the back way through this little forest and we have a taxi taking waiting for you.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:38.000
And that taxi, what you want to do is go to the train station and go straight to Andalusia, Andalusia, so that you stay away for a couple of weeks.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:49.000
So this whole thing will cool down. And then they'll forget about you. And I'm going, I am five feet ten inches. I am this color.

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:58.000
I had also gained a few pounds. I was so depressed. I was just eating at all hours. I know, okay, let me think about it.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:09.000
And I go back to my apartment. I do take the taxi back to my little apartment. And I wasn't supposed to be living in a apartment. I was supposed to be living in a pence on because I broke all the rules.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:26.000
And I found my friend who lived in a pence on a couple of blocks away. And she came over and she said, you know what, when, when I got back to my pence on, the woman who runs the pence on said that the police had been there looking for me.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:40.000
And this woman was a Franco sympathizer, but she told them to come back. Oh, she'll be back in four hours knowing that she would probably be back sooner. So she alerted us that the police were looking for us.

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:48.000
So we said, oh, the police are looking for us. What are we going to do? And so we call Carlos Blanco Aguina and he says come to our house.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:57.000
And so we pack up our suitcases and it's at an hour in Madrid where there aren't very many taxis. So we take this special kind of taxi and we have suitcases.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:09.000
And my friend who was with me was blonde and then there's me. And there was a third person on the list who was Carol Wattenawe, a Japanese girl from Hawaii, because she had done a few things with us.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:19.000
So we're in the cab going to the director's office and with our suitcases in the back and the guy is listening to the radio.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:32.000
And he heard the announcement comes on.

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:47.000
And so he looks the Chica de Colores, particularly exotic for Spain at that time. It was very provincial. So he looks at his rear view mirror. He doesn't say anything, but he drops us off.

00:55:47.000 --> 00:56:01.000
And so there we are at the director's house and we probably stayed there two or three days. It was very clear nobody's going to forget about us because they were making inquiries at the university.

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:10.000
There were different levels of sort of spies at the university repeatedly and the American Embassy as well was making inquiries. Where are they?

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:19.000
So we say, okay, let's just face the music. So we went back to our apartments. Well, she was in a pension. I was in a apartment.

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:28.000
So I get to my apartment and I'll leave out the story about eating my yogurt and walking past these people downstairs and all of that.

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:34.000
There was some guys and I just walked past them a couple of time and then eventually they come up and they say, not not.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:45.000
Are you a bird Alexander playing clothes? I say yes. And they say, well, we're the playing clothes police and we're supposed to take you in. I say, okay.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:54.000
And then we walk from my apartment to the Puerto del Sol. And we stop for coffee.

00:56:54.000 --> 00:57:07.000
For my apartment to the Puerto del Sol, which was mostly downhill and it was a central jail. And at the Puerto del Sol at the jail there, you go downstairs. It's like a dungeon.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:23.000
And I'm down there. I'm down there by myself because my friend hadn't gotten there yet. And somehow they had figured out the other prisoners because they had arrested a number of people because they were doing it before the May day.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:36.000
Demonstration so they did it preemptively. So there were a lot of people in the jail and they figured out that I was from the United States. I tried to pretend like I didn't speak Spanish. That didn't go anywhere though.

00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:41.000
And they started singing. We shall overcome.

00:57:41.000 --> 00:58:00.000
So to make that long story a little bit shorter, I was deported. But I think it was more like I was kidnapped by the Spanish state under the orders of the American State Department because everybody we asked said, I said, why are you arresting me?

00:58:00.000 --> 00:58:09.000
We don't know the American Embassy wants us to do it. They said that. They said that at every level. We don't know. We don't have anything to do with this.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:26.000
And we were put on a train. There was row of police with their, my friend obviously eventually showed up with their machine guns. At every stop, at every stop, there would be Guar they are civil, the guy who wore the funny hats.

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:46.000
Right outside our car. I mean, we were 20. And they took us to Idle. We crossed the border to Undy and Carlos Blanco was there waiting for us. He had made that trip. He had driven up to give us money and to set us up.

00:58:46.000 --> 00:59:00.000
So there's a little more to the story. We take the train to Paris and there were some immigrant workers like from Morocco. We're trying to tell them what happened to us and we're sharing food and there were some newspaper articles and we were trying to show them.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:20.000
And we get to Paris and I say, okay, everybody, you hand me your hand me your bags because we don't have money to pay anybody to help us. And there's a whole bunch of people gathered around. The guy comes up and he says, are you Roberta Alexander, Carol Wattena, Ben, Carol Wynn? And he said, yes. And he says, I'm from CBS.

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:42.000
And we have a limousine to take you to the Hotel Jacques Sank, which is the fanciest hotel in Paris. But what we need you to do is give us an interview tomorrow morning at 5.30 so that we can have it in the state for the evening news.

00:59:42.000 --> 01:00:04.000
And we said, okay, so then we take it off to the hotel Jacques Sank. It's a nice hotel. It was very, very, very, we were so fancy. We got to eat and all of that. And the one unfortunate thing is my parents somehow a radio station got through to me.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:21.000
A Los Angeles radio station got through to me when I was under house arrest during this whole bit because they took us out of jail and put us in house arrest. And I gave them an interview and my parents heard it because I hadn't been able to get hold of my parents.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:38.000
And then of course they see this on on well then I when I got to Paris I called them and then they see this interview on CBS and they were very proud. But there was reason to be afraid had it been Latin America it may not have turned out the same way.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:51.000
So they gave us a very kind of like human interest interview a very friendly interview and we got to New York and we came back and we got back to went straight back to Berkeley.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:56.000
How is the reception at Berkeley and the students following this?

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:10.000
Some people followed it. I was very disappointed in the people around the Du Bois Club and the Communist Party because they were not they were kind of like disinterested. I didn't see the I didn't see the fervor. It's about when I left.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:19.000
I was subsequently I went around and talked to Abraham Lincoln brigade people. My uncle was in the Abraham Lincoln brigade actually.

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:32.000
And so I talked to them and so then I don't know if they invited me to go to a celebration of the fall of the Nazis in Germany.

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:43.000
And they wanted each delegation to have one older person in a youth. And so these Abraham brigade these does you know so would you like to be the youth.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:54.000
So I went to this thing in East Germany and to speak it like something before you know three quarters of a million people.

01:01:54.000 --> 01:02:09.000
But it was a very very very interesting trip because what they did is they fed us wonderful food. We had translators but there was no good political conversation.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:23.000
It was just kind of dead. The only time I really had a good time was when I ran into some printers from Cuba. People who were studying printing in East Germany and they were from Cuba.

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:36.000
Well I could talk to them by myself for one and they were like full of you know this was 60, 67 and they were very enthusiastic and interested in talking about all of these ideas.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:44.000
But I got an idea of kind of what the Soviet block was like and it wasn't looking too good to me.

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:59.000
And then I spoke in front of a crowd these Germans you know they they timed everything you know your talk can be 75 seconds but don't sit down until the interpreter finishes because they're simultaneous.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:13.000
Yeah it's like Simon but it's not exactly so the German German takes much longer to say anything. And so the simultaneous interpreter would take a couple sentences longer when I finished I forgot and I sat down.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:28.000
The Soviet youth was about 50 years old you know and it was just all not looking too good to me so it changed my attitude toward that whole deal.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:31.000
So I came back to Berkeley.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:34.000
Okay, 1967 back to Berkeley.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:04:02.000
Okay 1967 back to Berkeley I completed oh I quit my associations with the Dubois Club and sort of the Communist Party group and I got involved with incredibly sectarian revolutionary quasi revolutionary intellectuals group for a little while.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:21.000
That didn't last and I found out and then I got into another one of those groups and the other one of those groups which wasn't quite as as narrow they says well we don't take black people black people have to join the Black Panther Party.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:43.000
That was the revolutionary union Bob Avaikian he was the leader and that was probably just as well was just a good thing. I had much better feelings at this point about the Black Panther Party than I had had previously because they started doing the community programs they started doing breakfast for school children and all of those kinds of programs.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:49.000
And I liked the ten point platform I thought it was relevant still a relevant today.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:53.000
What was your initial impression you said that it wasn't as positive at first?

01:04:53.000 --> 01:05:17.000
Well I just thought at first and this is really colored by a sort of narrow view of what's correct I just was not impressed by I had heard Bobby speak Bobby Seal speak and I was thinking about today.

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:31.000
I think we want our share of the pie or something like that and I thought well I'm a socialist I want to divide up the pie between everybody but actually you know our piece of the pie maybe wasn't that wrong in retrospect I mean I just didn't respond to it.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:46.000
So I started to be involved in the Black Panther Party by first going to the breakfast for school children program and it was at a church in Oakland and it was at the church.

01:05:46.000 --> 01:06:04.000
It was at the church where there's a famous photo of Charles Bussey you know serving people's Charles Burcy I think serving people eggs and bacon and we worked really hard and that was a lot of fun doing that you know getting up and cooking the food and then we also would go around asking for donations of the food.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:15.000
But the leadership of the party at that time they were pretty they were pretty sharp and they found out pretty quickly that I could spell I could type fast you know

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:36.000
and I was pretty well educated and so they assigned me to work on the Black Panther newspaper. So I was in the office I think it was shatic I think it was Berkeley was it's the but I was in the national office and it was technically Berkeley but I think it was considered the Oakland national office it was South Berkeley.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:53.000
And so that's where I met big man because he was the editor of the newspaper and that's where I spent a lot of time. Now if you're a Black Panther it's not like I go to a meeting a couple times a week it was full time.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:07:09.000
We pretty much gave our entire life we'd show up in the morning or people would have slept there all night and we get your assignments from the officer of the day who could have been a 17 year old you know deciding there was a woman named Martian 9.

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:24.000
I'm sure she was 17 when she was telling people okay you go here you go sell newspapers you do this you do that. So I did a little bit of everything I sold newspapers I did everything but basically I ended up working on the paper.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:50.000
And so big man would pick the articles and I would type them into the adjuster writer which was this old machine that would line it up and I would correct the spelling and put in a few periods that kind of thing and then about not about once a week we would go to the printers which was in San Francisco and what was the was the tenderloin district.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:08:10.000
And we would spend maybe 24 hours there laying out the paper you know because you have your copy and then you run it through this wax machine and then you could put it down and then you do your headlines and then Emory Douglas would show up who's the artist for the party I hope you're interviewing him.

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:34.000
You are now we are the artist for the party all of that art was Emory Douglas and he'd come in with different art things and he had a better eye of course for how to lay things out and and then we and then we go home exhausted and for some of that time I lived in North Richmond behind a church.

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:49.000
And for some of that time I lived in another area of North Richmond the reason I ended up in Richmond part of the reason was one of the problems that I had in the black Panther Party was being harassed by the guys.

01:08:49.000 --> 01:09:07.000
It was just being harassed you know it was kind of the thing like we're all revolutionaries and everything belongs to everybody including you know you should be doing some you know revolutionary sexual favors for me I did not buy that.

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:22.000
And I got into a relationship with a nice guy but in some ways it protected me as well so you know I liked him but there was also some protection his name was Bobby Bowen and he was from the Richmond area so.

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:36.000
Can we talk a little bit more about the gender relationships and the party yeah we got a few hours everybody's story will be different depending on where you were.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:10:03.000
Where you were and when you were there so I was there in 1969 Eldridge Cleaver was already gone and I had I wasn't impressed by his book so I'm nice somehow raping white women didn't seem like a revolutionary act to me although I could see that he was brilliant I had worked as an overseas operator for a while because I was working you know I worked in canaries and stuff because I was going to organize the industrial proletariat for a while.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:32.000
I worked as an operator and he had he had those kind of phones that you have on a boat and he was rude to us and you knew it was Eldridge Cleaver because who else is going to have a black accent you know with this over and out phone and all of the leadership when I was there they were men and he was in jail too so the people who were the leaders were Bobby Seal.

01:10:32.000 --> 01:11:01.000
David Hillyard, Masai, very important person, Hughitt Ray Hughitt and it was the three of them above all and Big Man was like the next tier but it was like this group and then there might be one or another coming in and they made the decision so they were smart they were very smart they had a lot of work to do.

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:24.000
They were very smart they had lots of interesting ideas they called the shots but there was like a class the vision they were up there drinking I don't know Shiva's regal and we were drinking bitter dog which was I'm sure you all know Tony Port and lemon juice and it actually tasted pretty good and it's probably gut rot but we were drinking it.

01:11:24.000 --> 01:11:44.000
Now go get some of the Shiva's regal and we're drinking it. Tony Port and lemon juice. That was one item and they all hit on me one or another time but David Hillyard was very persistent and I had a real problem with him.

01:11:44.000 --> 01:12:04.000
I was told to drive him home. Yeah, I was David. I was told to drive him home from something one night and he said well let's stop by your house I foolishly kind of did and I was supposed to be getting ribs ready for a picnic the next day.

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:23.000
One problem though is I didn't know how to do it forget my mom was white right moms with Jewish and my dad may have known how to do it but I didn't know so he makes his big deal makes fun to me whatever we get the ribs in oven because you get them cooked and then later you put them on the barbecue you don't cook them on a barbecue.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:44.000
And then he starts looking and then he's just very very uncomfortable and he makes a lot of advances and I say no no no no no and he doesn't force it so I drive him back to his mother's house in West Oakland and I go to the park to the picnic the next morning and all these people come up and say where's the chairman.

01:12:44.000 --> 01:13:11.000
Because everybody knew that he had gone home with me and I am inferring that everybody assumed that I had slept with him and he was coming back you know with me no I held I held the line on that I've subsequently been told that we saw we had agency with you Roberta of course I didn't know what they meant by agency but I mean this is far subsequently.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:21.000
You can be my agency well you have some control over what you do so that kind of stuff really bothered me but it stopped once I got into a relationship.

01:13:21.000 --> 01:13:35.000
Okay so okay then there's the big United Front Against Fascism in 19 it's in the summer of 1969 because I was in the party only in 1969.

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:58.000
They had figured out that I could give a pretty good speech I guess they had me doing political education classes and they asked me to speak at this event and it was in a big park and there were people came from all over the country I thought it might be a little premature to say it was the fascist country but it's okay.

01:13:58.000 --> 01:14:23.000
So I gave a speech about women at this United Front Against Fascism and Eldridge had come out with women are other half not are lesser half but are other half so that all sounded very good but I talked some about a little bit better than what he had been saying earlier perhaps saying and doing.

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:52.000
So I use that and I think I talked about relationships evolving and yes there's problems but with the brothers because part of the issue was there was the women's liberation movement and then there was questions whether or not women should be in the black panthers or should they be in the women's liberation movement because clearly you know there were all of these issues in the black panthers and I I believe that that time that the right place to be was in the black panthers.

01:14:52.000 --> 01:15:21.000
So I gave a speech after speech Angela Davis came up and introduced herself to me because she hadn't yet hit headlines and it was the strangest thing that she somebody just pitched the student at UCSD it was just like so strange but she told me Carlos Blanco Aguina got told her to introduce herself to me but after that

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:45.000
they decided at some point that big man and I would go to Japan together there was an invitation from the Zengap Korden and there were tickets so they decided to do this and I talked to my side and I said look my side I'm not going to talk straight nationalism because sometimes the panthers would be more nationalistic than other times.

01:15:45.000 --> 01:16:03.000
Most of the documents are international very very international but that wasn't always how everybody saw things and he said fine so I'm sort of the tag team with big man you know and so sometimes I'd say how big man we have to do it this way or we have to do it that way.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:32.000
So but before that happened we get to the airport in Tokyo and there's like some kind of cloak and daggers scene going on that we can't possibly understand but one group comes and they pick us up and they say hey we have to get out of here fast and we get on we get in some car and they're driving then this is big man's memory mostly so driving so fast and it's kind of scary.

01:16:32.000 --> 01:17:01.000
But anyway we find out a few days later that these people are misinterpreting what we were saying and that they were the red army and I don't know if you remember but the red army did stuff like blow up railroad tracks and that kind of stuff in black powder party was not doing that kind of thing and so we had to disassociate ourselves from then and it's very hard you can't read anything in Japan and you can't read anything.

01:17:02.000 --> 01:17:27.000
You can't hear any words that you might understand you know because it's a European language and so we got set up with a group that did films for the left and was called Ogawa Productions and they had relationships with everybody on the left and the left was very divided in Japan at the time.

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:47.000
The universities were occupied and then somebody be thrown off the fifth story or something like that but with these people we got around we also found out I don't know in my mind we realized but we should have known we only had one way tickets.

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:56.000
So we had to figure out a way to make some money so we tried to do we did that by charging for interviews.

01:17:56.000 --> 01:18:01.000
So what did you understand as your mission? I mean what was the point of the trip?

01:18:01.000 --> 01:18:16.000
You know that's a very good question. Our mission was that's very interesting. We saw our mission is to get out the story of the Black Panther Party and I think we also saw to learn about what's happening in Japan and come back and share it.

01:18:16.000 --> 01:18:21.000
And there were a lot of things happening in Japan that we were very unaware of.

01:18:21.000 --> 01:18:25.000
Were there others going to other countries? Were there the major trip?

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:35.000
Well this was an accident. See they somehow contacted the Black Panther Party National Headquarters and said we have a ticket and a lot of things I think happened like that.

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:49.000
1969 was a particularly chaotic year. The Panther Party had already grown so much. Something that I have not mentioned is that it was clearly infiltrated.

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:58.000
There was provocative tours going on. People will show up. Oh I just got out of prison. I want to join the party.

01:18:58.000 --> 01:19:07.000
In Richmond this guy came up to me. I was driving in my injury. A little white rambler. You know these would leave a little square innocent looking cars.

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:12.000
And he says yeah I want to put some knives in the trunk of your car for now. And I said no.

01:19:12.000 --> 01:19:22.000
And do you know the next morning on my way from North Richmond in this area that's completely abandoned before you can get on to the freeway going towards Berkeley and Oakland?

01:19:22.000 --> 01:19:35.000
I hear a siren. I pull over. And within 30 seconds there were seven or eight cars there. Screeching in. You know like. And they searched everything.

01:19:35.000 --> 01:19:42.000
And I don't think it was a coincidence that it happened the day after this guy wanted to put stuff.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:51.000
I wanted to get in my trunk. Put whatever he wanted in my trunk. I think I was pretty lucky to get out of that one.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:20:06.000
So they got an invitation to Japan. So we go to Japan. It happens to be that this journalist from Denmark comes and gets to know the black panthers and then they have a trip to Scandinavia.

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:16.000
And they're going to in the reunion. They're going to have a panel on foreign relations. Now there was other stuff that was much more official when they go to China.

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:31.000
They really met you know leaders in China and I guess in Algeria. They were recognized while you know while Eldridge was still part of the panthers before the split.

01:20:31.000 --> 01:20:39.000
So yeah. So we just okay you're going to go to Japan now. It wasn't like okay we want you to do this and that.

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:46.000
And I think that there may be at one time they would have been that organized but not in 1969.

01:20:46.000 --> 01:20:51.000
So what we did is we wanted to spread the message of what was happening with the black panther party.

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:58.000
We wanted to support the movements in Japan to the degree that we could figure out who's who.

01:20:58.000 --> 01:21:06.000
And then we had to earn our keep our earn our tickets. And so we actually had some very interesting trips.

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:23.000
We met with little old women who probably half my age now who were sitting in and sleeping in on American airport strips, military base airport strips.

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:36.000
We met the second and third sons of farmers because the system for inheriting land was the first son inherits land.

01:21:36.000 --> 01:21:47.000
Second and third then are pretty much a separate cast actually. And they would go to the cities and do construction work. People wouldn't marry them.

01:21:47.000 --> 01:22:04.000
It was very much a cast like system. And we met with the Korean immigrants and workers in Japan and had no idea that there were all of these things going on.

01:22:04.000 --> 01:22:13.000
The one place and this was thanks to these film these this film production company. They had relationships with all these people and they helped set it up.

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:22.000
We were followed the entire time except in my memory when we were with one particular interpreter.

01:22:22.000 --> 01:22:31.000
I mean they were Japanese guys and they were out there waiting. We catch a cab and they would follow us.

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:38.000
And once the cab wanted to tell us he didn't know where it was and we thought he was being racist and we insisted because you would write down what it was.

01:22:39.000 --> 01:22:47.000
And he was all up someplace and he stopped and asked and in the car behind stopped and asked you know where they're going and they just followed us.

01:22:47.000 --> 01:22:54.000
Everything we did was public but whatever we just you know followed.

01:22:54.000 --> 01:23:06.000
The one thing that everybody was united on at that time was to fight the construction of the new airport because it was on wonderful farming land.

01:23:06.000 --> 01:23:13.000
And there were already enough air bases that that could have been accommodated with some of these US air bases.

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:19.000
And there would be there were demonstrations of hundreds of thousands of people.

01:23:19.000 --> 01:23:29.000
And we spoke at that too. And it was really interesting because in their demonstrations you know the Japanese they lock arms and they tend to run.

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:36.000
But not everybody there's a role for everybody. So for the old folks they would collect night soil.

01:23:36.000 --> 01:23:47.000
You know what night soil is? They would collect night soil and the cops would run they would have a net over them to try to protect themselves from rocks and stuff but it didn't protect them from the night soil.

01:23:47.000 --> 01:23:56.000
And so they would be throwing this ship. It would go through. It was a real real problem and other people would be running.

01:23:56.000 --> 01:24:01.000
And I can't remember but when your demonstration is over since you're running most of the time you feel pretty good.

01:24:01.000 --> 01:24:07.000
You know I don't know how much was accomplished where they were massive demonstrations and we spoke there.

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:18.000
We also met with farmers, peasant farmers. And we saw a lot. We saw a lot of amazing things in Japan. When I got back.

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:20.000
So how long did you end up staying in Iraq?

01:24:20.000 --> 01:24:29.000
You know I think we were there at least a month. Maybe five weeks. I have the notes someplace. Some notes just where we had gone.

01:24:29.000 --> 01:24:37.000
And Big Man didn't come back with me. Big Man had to go to he went to Europe. He there was something he was supposed to do or tell.

01:24:37.000 --> 01:24:41.000
I don't know. There was something he was supposed to do. He didn't come back to me with me.

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:49.000
I get back and then of course they have a separate customs just for me with a Japanese guy there.

01:24:49.000 --> 01:25:01.000
And they asked for my telephone book and I said no you can't see my telephone book. And so whatever I got I got I got passed.

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:10.000
And so that was really the last big thing that I did in the party. I quit not too long after it.

01:25:10.000 --> 01:25:14.000
Was it easy to get out?

01:25:14.000 --> 01:25:27.000
I just walked away. Now but this is this is what happened. The whole time I look first of all there were levels of activities that I wasn't involved in in the Panthers.

01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:38.000
The office was metal plated and there were sandbags in the office. So I kind of and I want to remember that I'm kind of oblivious to all of this.

01:25:38.000 --> 01:25:48.000
And then there were other stuff. There was gun stuff going on and I was not part of it. They sent me to be trained to the shooting range or something.

01:25:48.000 --> 01:25:59.000
I shot a 357 Magnum one time. I thought my arm was going to fall off and I shot an F16 does that sound right?

01:25:59.000 --> 01:26:08.000
One time I thought my shoulder was going to fall off and it was noisy. I didn't want to have anything else to do with it and I did not.

01:26:08.000 --> 01:26:17.000
So I'm sure some of the people you're going to be talking to know much more about all of that but I really in a naive way didn't.

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:24.000
But what I did notice is about once every two weeks there would be fire engines on each side of our block.

01:26:24.000 --> 01:26:29.000
And one here and one there and that was kind of weird what's the fire engines there for.

01:26:29.000 --> 01:26:36.000
And then a newspaper it was not the Berkeley bar but another one. I don't remember the name but I have it somewhere.

01:26:36.000 --> 01:26:45.000
A Berkeley newspaper came found the Berkeley police plan for how they would vamp on the office.

01:26:45.000 --> 01:26:51.000
And one of the things that I remember actually you could find that on the internet now. I think that's where I found it.

01:26:51.000 --> 01:27:03.000
One of the things that I remember is that they would have the fire engines there because somehow they would blast their way into downstairs and then they would take these machine guns or whatever they are.

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:11.000
And they go like that. And then the upstairs would be on fire and I'd be up there typing that shit you know my little adjuster right here.

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:25.000
So I go wow you know I kind of saw you know this is this really is. I mean I had been writing Fred Hampton hadn't been killed yet but so many people had been arrested that year.

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:38.000
So many office had been vamped on. I don't know but reading this made it really come home. And so one I did not want to die for the Black Panther Party.

01:27:38.000 --> 01:27:53.000
One, two I felt the party was infiltrated and a lot of times you know those infiltrators are the ones that bring you the guns and encourage or even carry out some of the crazier activities.

01:27:53.000 --> 01:28:01.000
I never had in my mind a way to have a revolution that we could shoot our way into in this country that could be done through violence.

01:28:01.000 --> 01:28:11.000
Even though I got a revolutionary terms and all that violence part of it I never you know can't even shoot a gun.

01:28:11.000 --> 01:28:23.000
And third I was pregnant and I did not was not ready to take the responsibility of having a child.

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:43.000
And so for those three reasons I told them I'm going to go visit my parents but I didn't come back. Subsequently David Hilliard figured out where who had my all my books because I had this huge library you know Mao and then all the revolution marks and stuff.

01:28:43.000 --> 01:28:48.000
And he came in intimidated those folks and took all my books.

01:28:48.000 --> 01:29:06.000
So the one thing is I think this was a period in the party where there was like a purge kind of thing going on so somebody would leave and they call them a running dog lackey several other words they never published anything like that about me.

01:29:06.000 --> 01:29:22.000
I sent them everything I had from the Japan trip and I was sorry that I did that but somehow subsequently a lot of that's been recovered because we had a woman who was doing research on that project for us and she she found out a lot of that information.

01:29:22.000 --> 01:29:27.000
So then I was back in the United States and with my parents.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:40.000
I lived there for a year and I talked to Carlos Blanco because I was at doing a typing job at that point and he says come down to San Diego because we are starting third college.

01:29:40.000 --> 01:29:42.000
Can we stop for a minute?

01:29:42.000 --> 01:29:47.000
Sure. Bring it back to where we stopped which was third college in San Diego.

01:29:47.000 --> 01:29:52.000
Okay so I gave you the wrong name it was in Lumumba Sapata College.

01:29:52.000 --> 01:30:13.000
Okay so what had happened in fall of 68 and 69 is students at that college including Angela Davis and African American students and the Chicano students they got together and they said we want a college that

01:30:13.000 --> 01:30:19.000
that will teach us our history as well as white students were involved in it as well.

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:22.000
And these are students who are originally at San Diego State?

01:30:22.000 --> 01:30:36.000
They were already at UCSD because the way they were developing UCSD was to have colleges so that the university wouldn't feel so inhumane or you know there'd be an intimate touch.

01:30:36.000 --> 01:30:51.000
And they actually and this is when there was a lot of organizing going around all over for ethnic studies departments and all of that and I went to a lot of those demonstrations I do remember those.

01:30:51.000 --> 01:31:01.000
And they were granted Lumumba Sapata College but that was that temporary name.

01:31:01.000 --> 01:31:10.000
So the university called it third college so when I called Carlos Blanco he says come down we can get you a job at third college.

01:31:10.000 --> 01:31:13.000
So what am I 23?

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:19.000
They have me interview for the resident dean position.

01:31:19.000 --> 01:31:26.000
And the people on the interviewing committee are students and a couple of other people.

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:36.000
And they give me the job of resident dean of third college the first year of its existence.

01:31:36.000 --> 01:31:39.000
Start at the top.

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:47.000
Yeah so okay so to be resident dean one of the perks is you have this house.

01:31:47.000 --> 01:31:52.000
And around the house which is you know like a 70s flat house.

01:31:52.000 --> 01:31:56.000
And all around the house are the big dorms.

01:31:56.000 --> 01:32:09.000
And they've been doing recruiting of students to come to third college at all levels but especially the freshman level and recruiting faculty and staff administrators.

01:32:09.000 --> 01:32:12.000
Okay so far so good.

01:32:12.000 --> 01:32:22.000
But from the very beginning this effort was infiltrated.

01:32:22.000 --> 01:32:38.000
So that there were a couple of administrators who the university insisted be hired even though the committee, the so-called you know committee led by students faculty and staff didn't want that person to be.

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:43.000
They insisted some of these people be hired.

01:32:43.000 --> 01:32:56.000
And this individual stood up at the very first meeting and started talking about the black people don't have the same you know this is not serving black people.

01:32:56.000 --> 01:32:59.000
This is just serving you whites and chicanos.

01:32:59.000 --> 01:33:03.000
And so it was very divisive from the very beginning.

01:33:03.000 --> 01:33:15.000
And here I am in this fish bowl with the students around and amongst the student body the same thing had already happened.

01:33:15.000 --> 01:33:21.000
In fact there were guys kind of very similar to some of them who showed up in the black Panther party.

01:33:21.000 --> 01:33:33.000
The prison you know the kind of they stare at you and they never take their eye away because that's how they've learned to behave you know and to intimidate and to be the alpha individual.

01:33:33.000 --> 01:33:36.000
There were there were those.

01:33:36.000 --> 01:33:43.000
And I very early on was attacked because look at my background.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:52.000
You know I grew up in Latino area. I've been in the black Panther party. I've been to Spain. I danced with my progressive friends.

01:33:52.000 --> 01:34:03.000
I even sing folk music you know and I was attacked for having relationships with everybody.

01:34:03.000 --> 01:34:12.000
I was even told at a BSU meeting black student meeting Robert as far as we know you like chicanos but you like black people.

01:34:12.000 --> 01:34:16.000
You know was that kind of thing. It was extremely divisive.

01:34:16.000 --> 01:34:22.000
And we had courses like third world studies. We had some fabulous professors.

01:34:22.000 --> 01:34:34.000
And I don't think there was a university in this country that had to the degree that we had at that amount of control had that potential to be something fabulous.

01:34:34.000 --> 01:34:42.000
But I'm quite sure it was probably part of the Coentel program just like the Panthers that suffered from the Coentel program.

01:34:42.000 --> 01:34:49.000
There was no doubt about it and it turned into like I have a tendency when things are really bad to forget.

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:57.000
But I was threatened one night at gunpoint and I left and I went to Carlos Blanco's house.

01:34:57.000 --> 01:35:08.000
He just keeps coming up and they go, Roberta don't you remember this is what they said they said they're going to get you and stuff and that's why you.

01:35:08.000 --> 01:35:13.000
It was a very difficult time.

01:35:13.000 --> 01:35:18.000
So I quit after nine months because among other things I was not a good resident dean.

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:23.000
I was supposed to be putting on dances and things and I was supposed to say oh you broke a window.

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:28.000
Okay your family is going to have to pay for it and all that kind of stuff.

01:35:28.000 --> 01:35:33.000
And I was awful. It was absolutely awful. It was the wrong job. I didn't like it.

01:35:33.000 --> 01:35:36.000
I actually probably quit before I was going to get fired.

01:35:36.000 --> 01:35:42.000
So I quit and I applied to two places for graduate school.

01:35:42.000 --> 01:35:50.000
I applied to the School of Education at Harvard because they had sent me some advertisement when I was a senior at Berkeley.

01:35:50.000 --> 01:35:55.000
And I applied to the Literature Department at UCSD.

01:35:55.000 --> 01:36:03.000
Well Harvard offered me a full scholarship to be in their master's program and I figured that wasn't going to make it because it was cold back there.

01:36:03.000 --> 01:36:09.000
And I was a little insulted. And so I did the program at UCSD.

01:36:09.000 --> 01:36:12.000
I got a PhD in comparative literature.

01:36:12.000 --> 01:36:16.000
Let me ask you one quick question. It's going back for just a second.

01:36:16.000 --> 01:36:27.000
Did you, because you were talking about folks challenging you sort of on the variety of your interests and your background while at the third college.

01:36:27.000 --> 01:36:31.000
Did this come up in the Black Panther Party as well at all?

01:36:31.000 --> 01:36:34.000
You know not so much but it came up around food.

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:37.000
So you heard my story about the ribs.

01:36:37.000 --> 01:36:42.000
So in the, no, there were a lot of light skin.

01:36:42.000 --> 01:36:45.000
There were a number of light skinned people.

01:36:45.000 --> 01:36:52.000
There is antagonism based on skin color in the Black community.

01:36:52.000 --> 01:37:01.000
And people who are lighter skinned are seen as more privileged and some people find it more attractive or all that kind of stuff.

01:37:01.000 --> 01:37:04.000
And there's a long history of that in this country.

01:37:04.000 --> 01:37:09.000
That didn't make itself apparent to me while I was in the Black Panther Party.

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:17.000
But having been raised by a Jewish mom who wasn't even that good a cook, we once in a while had to cook for everybody.

01:37:17.000 --> 01:37:24.000
So me and this other girl and her name was, I want to say shelly. Her name was Shelly.

01:37:24.000 --> 01:37:31.000
And she was very light skinned and her, and clearly her mom was white too, it was one of those things.

01:37:31.000 --> 01:37:33.000
And we had to cook.

01:37:33.000 --> 01:37:51.000
So I had a specialty which was tuna casserole that comes out of the joy of cooking book with Kellogg's, not frosted, but flakes that you put on top to give it that little crunch and probably cream a mushroom soup.

01:37:51.000 --> 01:37:58.000
No. That did not go over me and Shelly where the only people eating that thing.

01:37:58.000 --> 01:38:07.000
Nobody touched it. We heard about it. We heard about it later.

01:38:07.000 --> 01:38:09.000
I did my best.

01:38:09.000 --> 01:38:11.000
What's this man is?

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:27.000
But you know another contradiction for me I'll be honest. You know, it's very often there were so many times when African American men would be with white women, especially in the educated zone, you know, that I would kind of like.

01:38:27.000 --> 01:38:30.000
And yeah, but that's kind of hard because my mom's white.

01:38:30.000 --> 01:38:36.000
So there is that it's a very, very, very complicated dynamic.

01:38:36.000 --> 01:38:46.000
And working on the project that I've been working on recently I hear a little bit about it sometimes. It's not hostile, but you know, that's a dynamic and it's out there.

01:38:46.000 --> 01:38:50.000
Status based on skin color.

01:38:50.000 --> 01:38:55.000
Well, thank you for answering that. So back to, so starting your graduate program.

01:38:55.000 --> 01:39:03.000
Right. So that was just a lot of fun. You know, it was a graduate program. At that time there were there were grants.

01:39:03.000 --> 01:39:13.000
I got a Ford grant, which you know, if you read Naomi Klein, you know, was a lot dirtier than I may have thought of, but they didn't influence what I was doing.

01:39:13.000 --> 01:39:27.000
And I got a PhD in comparative literature, but I probably was in the wrong area because my my dissertation was the fictional portrayal of popular movements.

01:39:27.000 --> 01:39:37.000
So I read these different books, you know, about Haiti and Cuba and Mexico and the United States about slave rebellions and revolutions.

01:39:37.000 --> 01:39:54.000
And that's whatever it was about. But then after I got that degree, I only played to one college and I recognized that I didn't want to be in the academy.

01:39:54.000 --> 01:40:07.000
You know, I didn't want to have that publish or perish and the kind of competition that I saw within faculty members and, you know, the that whole process.

01:40:07.000 --> 01:40:20.000
And so I actually started teaching adult school for a while. And I taught adult school mostly ESL for and a lot of refugees from Vietnam for about 12 years.

01:40:20.000 --> 01:40:28.000
And that was interesting too to hear their stories because that forced me to see things in a little more complex way.

01:40:28.000 --> 01:40:39.000
And then fortunately I was recruited to organize the ESL program at city college. And that's where I was for the last 25 years.

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:52.000
And I feel like at city college, my contribution was primarily becoming the department chair. And I was there at the time for the English department.

01:40:52.000 --> 01:41:08.000
And I was there at a time when I could really turn around the composition of the faculty so that we have increasingly diverse faculty, a progressive faculty and a very dedicated faculty and the department functions well.

01:41:08.000 --> 01:41:19.000
And that's quite a good legacy because there's a lot of non-functioning dysfunctional English departments out there in every other kind of department.

01:41:19.000 --> 01:41:29.000
So that was good. But also at city college, I also was responsible for about four or five years for the labor studies program.

01:41:29.000 --> 01:41:41.000
It was a program that was floundering for a while. It's always a difficult program to make successful in San Diego.

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:50.000
And so we offered an AA, an associate's degree in labor studies. And so it would be a class in the history of labor.

01:41:50.000 --> 01:42:06.000
And now there is a class I wasn't involved with that in organizing. And then there's lots of classes like workers, compensation and disability and a lot of things about law, you know, and how to be as well as leadership classes.

01:42:06.000 --> 01:42:18.000
And I introduced the occupational safety and health classes. And those are very important. And we got a bigger variety of people to come to those classes.

01:42:18.000 --> 01:42:30.000
And we worked with people from the UCLA labor program to organize those. And people from up there came down to teach a number of those classes.

01:42:30.000 --> 01:42:41.000
One of the reasons I think it's difficult is because I'm not sure the leadership of all the unions really want to develop the next generation to take their place.

01:42:41.000 --> 01:42:46.000
That's one. Now that would be different for different locals and different leaders.

01:42:46.000 --> 01:43:02.000
Another one is as many of them have their built-in classes that they give for shop stewards or whatever. So there's some, you know, overlap or redundancy.

01:43:02.000 --> 01:43:21.000
Yeah, so that is one of the one of the struggles I used to go to the meetings of the Central Labor Council regularly. And they would say this is good. This is good. This is good. This is good. But then they didn't send the people to the classes. So it's always a struggle to keep your classes.

01:43:21.000 --> 01:43:49.000
Class is full. Now there is a labor studies program in Los Angeles. L.A. Trade Tech, I believe, which is very successful. And you know, we're trying to follow some of his examples. But it hasn't taken off. So anytime there's a fallen enrollment, we have a fall there. However, they are doing some very interesting things. Now they're developing internships for people. And they're working with CPI.

01:43:49.000 --> 01:43:52.000
Is it Stanford?

01:43:52.000 --> 01:43:54.000
Center for Policy Initiative.

01:43:54.000 --> 01:44:04.000
Yeah. It's local Center for Policy and Initiative. And so they're getting a lot of really good hands-on experience and they're getting paid for doing it as well.

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:18.000
So there is pretty good cohort of people who are going through that. So those, you know, that covers 25 years of my life. But there was a lot of work. And I felt it was I was able to do productive, really good things there.

01:44:18.000 --> 01:44:34.000
I also taught in the Chicano Studies program. Yeah, and there was a little bit of, you know, there was a little bit of conflict. But yeah, you know, some people wanted to keep me out. But she had no reason that the administrator to do so.

01:44:34.000 --> 01:44:43.000
I says, if you don't want me to do it because I'm not Chicano, just say that and I won't do it. You know, because, you know, but that wasn't it. She, oops, did I miss something up?

01:44:43.000 --> 01:44:57.000
Yeah, you know, it didn't turn out to be a problem. Actually, that was one of my favorite places. Black studies I would have liked to have taught, but it just didn't work out. Just didn't work out because that was the big English person.

01:44:57.000 --> 01:45:12.000
Did third college survive? Yes. Innocence. It's now called Third Good Marshall. And I think most of the curriculum, you know, there's some still there are still some elements from third college.

01:45:12.000 --> 01:45:19.000
But it certainly is not the revolution experiment. The revolutionary experiment that it started out to be. Not the limo sabata.

01:45:19.000 --> 01:45:41.000
It's not the limo sabata. I don't know that it's serving Latino, African-American and poor folks population in the same sense. Yeah. I mean, look at the, you know, when I went to Berkeley, there was not even 1% African-American, right?

01:45:41.000 --> 01:45:48.000
I think we're getting close to that too. And on the UCSD campuses, I mean, it's very, very low.

01:45:48.000 --> 01:46:03.000
So it's fall, it was up and falling as falling. Was it up higher? Yeah, for a while it was up higher. Well, with third college and with affirmative action, but that has fallen to as low as it was in 1964 on some of these campuses.

01:46:03.000 --> 01:46:18.000
I have a lot of Asian, but yeah, they do not have that kind of representation. They do have quite a lot more Latino and Chicano. But see, college is very mixed.

01:46:18.000 --> 01:46:25.000
It's still much more heavily Latino now because that's what's happening with the demographic.

01:46:25.000 --> 01:46:41.000
But yeah, no, we've gone back. We've gone back. I mean, to think that the packing houses are in many respects, just as bad as they were when my father was working there in 1932 or something.

01:46:41.000 --> 01:47:00.000
And not in unions. To look at the police brutality that we have now and the murders, just as well. I don't have, my tongue was happening in the South, but in Oakland, California.

01:47:00.000 --> 01:47:05.000
It's similar to where we are now.

01:47:05.000 --> 01:47:18.000
Not very true. But there is some good stuff. All right, there's some good stuff that I think is very important. And I don't think it's just unique to San Diego, but it is a little bit unique to San Diego.

01:47:18.000 --> 01:47:29.000
There is a community organization called Pillars of the Community, and I'm now relatively active in at least one aspect of that organization.

01:47:29.000 --> 01:47:42.000
It's a faith-based organization, but you're Muslim. See, my family, we got the Black, we got to Jewish, and pretty much the only thing that was left that people would be mad at would be the Muslim.

01:47:42.000 --> 01:47:52.000
So my son decided to fix that, and he converted to Islam a long time ago, 20 years ago.

01:47:53.000 --> 01:48:12.000
So now I got the Muslim thing, and so I got grandson's, whose mother's from Gujarat, Gujarat is an interesting place to be Muslim. So I got Urdu speaking grandson's, who wear their kufi, and then I've been to weddings with the Yamaha.

01:48:12.000 --> 01:48:14.000
We got it all covered. What's left?

01:48:14.000 --> 01:48:22.000
Oh, God, yeah, that's right. In the Native American stuff. Yeah. So our family kind of just happened that way.

01:48:22.000 --> 01:48:33.000
So it's a faith-based organization, but there's a lot of people who are not Muslim, who are served by the organization and also work with in it.

01:48:33.000 --> 01:48:45.000
They have a storefront in Encanto in Southeast San Diego, which is not unlike the Black Panther storefronts that we used to have except this one doesn't have two stories.

01:48:45.000 --> 01:48:55.000
And there's a lot of community activities that take place. Just be probably more prepared to go through all of them.

01:48:55.000 --> 01:49:05.000
One of the, one of the infacies is helping people who get out of prison, adjust and succeed in life outside of prison.

01:49:05.000 --> 01:49:13.000
Other things that they're doing is they're organizing within the community to get people more politically active.

01:49:13.000 --> 01:49:24.000
A major thrust of campaign now is the San Diego 33 campaign. And that's because in the whole state of California, I'm not sure the whole state of California is aware of this.

01:49:24.000 --> 01:49:40.000
There's a penal code, penal code, 182.5. And that penal code is the gang documentation. And it's based on one of these California initiatives that got passed in the early 2000s.

01:49:40.000 --> 01:49:54.000
And it says, if you have, if they can demonstrate that you've done two or three things, then they can say you are a gang member.

01:49:54.000 --> 01:50:06.000
So those two or three things can be, if you happen to be wearing the color green, if you happen to be standing in your neighborhood in front of your grandmother's house, which somebody decided is a gang house.

01:50:06.000 --> 01:50:17.000
If you happen to be taken to a gang member, which could be your neighbor, right? That's enough. And God forbid you do rap and put it on the internet, right? That's enough.

01:50:17.000 --> 01:50:30.000
You're a, you're a documented gang member, but you don't know that. And the documented gang members are from the ages of eight, ages of nine up.

01:50:30.000 --> 01:50:47.000
And there's thousands of them in the state of California. And so the district attorney in San Diego got it in her head that she's going to test this out.

01:50:47.000 --> 01:51:02.000
So she arrests 33 African American men about two years ago, including Aaron Harvey and Brandon, Brandon Duncan.

01:51:02.000 --> 01:51:10.000
Aaron Harvey at the time was in Las Vegas, getting ready to study real estate and become a rich guy, so in his real estate.

01:51:10.000 --> 01:51:21.000
And he hears all these helicopters and shit and they, and they land in the machine guns and sweat and he goes out and he says, you guys making too much noise. You must lost your guy by now.

01:51:21.000 --> 01:51:36.000
Whoever you're looking for is long gone. And then it turned out they were looking for him. And what am I charged with? And there's this whole series of violent and events in San Diego. You're charged with all this.

01:51:36.000 --> 01:51:50.000
He says, I wasn't even in San Diego. We know you weren't in San Diego, but you're a documented gang member and a gang carried it out. And we're going to put you in jail and we're charging you with all of these things.

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:57.000
Did it include murder? No, not cases shooting shootings.

01:51:57.000 --> 01:52:10.000
And jail for seven months, they know perfectly well he had nothing to do with it and didn't have and didn't even know about it. And he says, well, what do I get out of it?

01:52:10.000 --> 01:52:22.000
Why me? He says, because your reputation went up with these, you know, with this violence or whatever your street cred or whatever. And he's not even living in San Diego.

01:52:22.000 --> 01:52:44.000
So I don't know why they wanted to mess with him because his family came together and they joined forces with the pillars of the community and reclaiming the community and another project, which is broader than pillars in San Diego and did not just let him be stuck in jail.

01:52:44.000 --> 01:52:59.000
Because what most people do, they do not have legal resources and they make plea bargain because they're facing 50 years in prison. And they say, well, you just say guilty and will give you eight or whatever.

01:52:59.000 --> 01:53:01.000
So they admit to something that they did not do.

01:53:01.000 --> 01:53:04.000
People admit actually admit to because they're terrified.

01:53:04.000 --> 01:53:19.000
So one young man with 19 or so he signed a case of an anti-cancelor case. He was actually on Facebook, but he signed his own idea to be serving the country.

01:53:19.000 --> 01:53:32.000
And he didn't know how to connect. So between the family community and their own good sense, they didn't sign a deal and they spent seven months in jail.

01:53:32.000 --> 01:53:42.000
Being shackled, being handcuffed, going back and forth to jury cases and so forth, and finally being free.

01:53:42.000 --> 01:53:51.000
But as a consequence of that, there is a pretty decent movement in San Diego now addressing these police activities.

01:53:51.000 --> 01:54:02.000
So pillars of the community is involved in that. They also do things like workshops, what are your rights if you get stopped? What can you do? What should you not do? What you don't have to do?

01:54:02.000 --> 01:54:06.000
And all of that and what the consequences are.

01:54:06.000 --> 01:54:21.000
And two years ago, when I was a two years ago, my son, the Muslim, came up with the idea to do a rap CD because he's of the brand that doesn't even listen to music, little rap.

01:54:21.000 --> 01:54:39.000
And they have connections with so many relationships with so many community folks that they got a major rapper from San Diego to put together a rap album that was a meaningful rap album to speak to the people in the streets who like listening to rap.

01:54:39.000 --> 01:54:47.000
Now when I put it on, it's still rap and it's kind of hard to listen to, but it's a community activity.

01:54:47.000 --> 01:55:08.000
So then where I'm involved is, wasn't the rap album or the sound technician or anything, but another program we started last summer was just getting people together to write their story, any aspect of their own story that they want to do, but make it a story, not your whole long life.

01:55:08.000 --> 01:55:22.000
And then the goal of doing that would be we would invite your family and some friends, small gathering, we weren't looking at 500 people, didn't want that.

01:55:22.000 --> 01:55:29.000
And friends, and you would read it to them. And we've done that three different times with three different groups.

01:55:29.000 --> 01:55:45.000
And it is an amazing process to go through, absolutely amazing, because these people, we didn't ask them to, but they all found, sometimes they're most traumatic incident in their life.

01:55:45.000 --> 01:55:55.000
And sometimes they're most, a moment of achievement and then awareness of where they had been.

01:55:55.000 --> 01:56:08.000
And so coincidentally, not exactly on purpose, it's all people of color, more or less, I mean it's all African American, it's Chicano, and we work together, everybody work together.

01:56:08.000 --> 01:56:17.000
And you have to trust, because you're trying to write, you read it to somebody else, and somebody else tells you what they think, and maybe you can make this a letter, it'll work.

01:56:17.000 --> 01:56:26.000
And so there are all kinds of stories, some of them are neglect, some of them are seeing your mother murdered in front of you.

01:56:26.000 --> 01:56:46.000
What one of them is that, some is being bussed to another school system, and what that does to your morale, you know, if you get bussed to like a white school, education things, one was an incredible education achievement, the guy had background prison and breaking the law and all kinds of stuff.

01:56:46.000 --> 01:57:12.000
Aaron Harvey, one of the important people who, important in that, he's gone so public and brought the issue public for the San Diego 33, wrote a story about visiting his uncle in jail, and then he's gone with his mother, and then the second part of the story, it's him who's in jail.

01:57:12.000 --> 01:57:33.000
And pretty much the same scenario. People with some serious prison experiences, I mean, I learned, I had to say, you know, I don't know what it's like, you know, to live in a family where your parents are drug addicts, and what did that look like? What was it like when you guys came home?

01:57:33.000 --> 01:57:54.000
You know, so I learned so much, and at the same time, these are people who are thriving and struggling to thrive. I mean, they're struggling with life now. It's not easy. Coincidentally, at least half of them are related to to city college and one way or another.

01:57:54.000 --> 01:58:10.000
I have a Palestinian colleague who was actually helped start that program, and she just gave a story about how, well, if you, people say, where are you from? She said, I'm from Detroit. No, where are you really from?

01:58:10.000 --> 01:58:28.000
You know, and then how she's gotten stereotyped and sort of branded and how that's an issue for folks and how to identify yourself and what the reactions are. So it's a wide variety. So, okay, so these people read their stories, and that was very successful.

01:58:28.000 --> 01:58:38.000
And then we thought in the opportunity, because here we have a press called City Works Press, and it's an independent press, and now those stories are going to get published.

01:58:38.000 --> 01:58:52.000
Yeah. And Erica, I'm not sure if she's going to get it in on time, because we have to get it. They said she would write a blurb. Big man wrote a wonderful blurb about it and how important it is to get these stories out.

01:58:52.000 --> 01:59:08.000
And I don't know if you know Jimmy Santiago Blackout or Luis Rodriguez. Both of them, they are very important Chicano writers, and one of them had experience with gangs, the other one, a lot of experience with prisons and stuff, and that's what they wrote about.

01:59:08.000 --> 01:59:29.000
And we teach them a lot in our classes. And so it's really an exciting project. We're going to pick it up again and see where it goes. So it's modest, but altogether we included everybody who wanted to be included in the publishing part. We included everybody, 19 authors.

01:59:29.000 --> 01:59:44.000
So there's one very explicit connection there, talking about the blurbs with the Black Panther Party, but can you tell me about, have there been other opportunities for sort of bringing in lessons of your own experience, the Black Panther Party to the work that's going on in San Diego now?

01:59:44.000 --> 02:00:01.000
You know, I've gone to classes, pretty much. I've gone to classes. And then last year, and I've talked to classes and given presentations, I'm being asked to be involved in a panel at San Diego State. I've spoken twice at UCSD.

02:00:01.000 --> 02:00:24.000
And it was usually at times when there was organization going on. Once shortly after there were some awful incidents in UCSD, I don't know if you're familiar with them, but there was like, I don't know, effigies of like, no, not effigy, cook, clucks, but very threatening kinds of stuff. Do you remember what it?

02:00:24.000 --> 02:00:48.000
Yeah, they had this so-called comp through. Nooses on the campus. Yeah. And then graffiti, you know, anti-Black graffiti. So I've spoken at UCSD a few times, and I have those things coming up when Big Man came down, I presented him and spoke to those. And yeah, that's pretty much the extent.

02:00:48.000 --> 02:01:13.000
I'm not a star. I, you know, I just happen to be in a lot of places. No, I'm not a star. I just, been in some places. I've done things my life where I didn't know what the risks were. Always. Yeah, I was in the Panthers for a year, serious year.

02:01:13.000 --> 02:01:23.000
And I met some people who I respect very, very much, but I did not establish the ongoing relationships, particularly with women.

02:01:23.000 --> 02:01:35.000
Part of the problem with the Panthers, one of the problems, we didn't take care of ourselves, you even hear this from America Huggins. We did not take care of ourselves. We were just running all the time. And some of that included personal relations.

02:01:35.000 --> 02:01:46.000
And I'm talking only about my year, 1969 in Oakland headquarters. I cannot speak for what was going on in every place else. And later.

02:01:46.000 --> 02:01:50.000
So how did that manifest when you said not taking care of yourselves?

02:01:50.000 --> 02:01:58.000
Well, part of what I was thinking about is not taking care of ourselves is for me anyway, having good relationships with other women in the party.

02:01:58.000 --> 02:02:09.000
There just wasn't any time. You're just running around all the time. Or you go home and sleep. If you had your own home or you'd sleep there, we were always doing something.

02:02:09.000 --> 02:02:22.000
So, for example, I don't think I spoke to anybody else about the sexual harassment. Now, that seems a little silly. You know, that's, that it shouldn't have been that way.

02:02:22.000 --> 02:02:33.000
So, I think that the stress or mental health repercussions of being in the high stress life situation.

02:02:33.000 --> 02:02:46.000
You know, I never thought about it. I think my way to deal with high stress is to forget. Like the details, I think my highest stress was actually third college, believe it or not.

02:02:46.000 --> 02:02:58.000
And I've forgotten the details. I've forgotten. I can just tell you, you know, Carlos Blanco and his entire family tells me that I was threatened by guns. I would not have said.

02:02:58.000 --> 02:03:05.000
I would say somebody was intimidating me and I left, but I didn't remember the guns and everybody else did.

02:03:05.000 --> 02:03:18.000
So, it's kind of like, yeah, there's an emotional toll. But I think I just sort of suppressed that emotional toll and keep on keeping on.

02:03:18.000 --> 02:03:34.000
There's an emotional toll also. You know, I always said, oh, well, those people who say, I had a teacher in high school. And he said, it was like some stupid class, like, I don't know, social adjustment or something.

02:03:34.000 --> 02:03:49.000
And this was a light skinned black guy. He wore some kind of two-pain and looked like shoe polished us on the back of his head. And one day he said, the kids who are worst adjusted are the ones who are born out of wedlock.

02:03:49.000 --> 02:04:01.000
Well, for sure, I was born out of wedlock because it was illegal to be married and mixed race. And I said, oh, he's crazy because I have the advantage of being both and the born out of wedlock, well, that never gave me trouble.

02:04:01.000 --> 02:04:17.000
But being mixed race in a time of identity politics is a problem. And I have to be really honest. I got a lot of Jewish in me. I was very close to my grandmother.

02:04:17.000 --> 02:04:26.000
You know, I walk through the world as African-American. I'm fine with that. My grandmother even would ask me, I said, I got a boyfriend. She would say, is he Jewish?

02:04:26.000 --> 02:04:43.000
You know, it's just there. So when we're talking about Israel and Palestine, yes, my grandmother was very upset with Israeli policies regarding Palestine. Very upset.

02:04:43.000 --> 02:04:56.000
And she would be in arguments with all her Jewish old lady friends all the time about that. But then I don't want to hear anything that sounds a little bit like anti-Semitic.

02:04:56.000 --> 02:05:06.000
You know, even though I might even be getting kidded by my Muslim grandkids or whatever. No, what do you tell me? You got to understand the history of the Jews.

02:05:06.000 --> 02:05:24.000
And yes, what there, what large aspects of the government is doing now is really bad. But don't forget, there's people in Israel who don't agree. And they have to be pretty brave if they're fighting against this mainstream. So this is what, so I'm always navigating that.

02:05:24.000 --> 02:05:41.000
I do not like to go to anything that's strictly racial based. I don't go to the African-American faculty staff meetings. So kind of over that. And I don't go to the 100% Chicano things. And I'm always invited. I'm always invited to those things.

02:05:41.000 --> 02:06:00.000
And it's probably stupid of me not to go. But I don't want to go to anything that's so racially, that's so racially based. That's just, you know, I think that's not the pan. Well, part of it, you know, the Panthers was interesting about the Panthers is they did reach out to other groups.

02:06:00.000 --> 02:06:23.000
It wasn't, yes, we want to be a black group. But we want to reach out to other groups, not, you know, attack them and fight over the crumbs. And I think that's very, that that's, that's very important. And they did do that. And once in a while nationalism would come in. But there's reasons for black people to have a chip on their shoulder.

02:06:23.000 --> 02:06:30.000
You know, it's have to discuss why that's there. If we, if chip on the shoulder is the right expression, it's not.

02:06:33.000 --> 02:06:38.000
Wonderful. Well, I think I got most of it.

02:06:38.000 --> 02:06:50.000
I think we could talk for hours more and would love to do that. But we should probably start to wrap up. Is there something that, is there anything that you thought I was going to ask that I didn't ask?

02:06:50.000 --> 02:06:56.000
They should have asked today in the conversation.

02:06:56.000 --> 02:07:05.000
I'll think of that tonight.

02:07:05.000 --> 02:07:13.000
We covered a lot of territory.

02:07:13.000 --> 02:07:28.000
I would just like to add that my sister also is pretty much dedicated her life to health care, African American community, and has organized a lot of things.

02:07:28.000 --> 02:07:42.000
My brother, because she became a medical doctor, and neither of our parents had gone to college. My brother became, he, he actually suffered the most in the McCarthy period.

02:07:42.000 --> 02:07:54.000
The FBI even came and visited him in San Luis Obispo when he was in college and everything. So he kind of stayed away from that activist kind of thing, but he came the CEO of, no, no.

02:07:54.000 --> 02:08:05.000
The chief medical officer of Kaiser, of a whole section of Kaiser and Los Angeles. And I think he actually changed the culture of the hospital.

02:08:05.000 --> 02:08:12.000
At least that's how people talked. And they, they, they, and they talk to us.

02:08:12.000 --> 02:08:21.000
When Dr. Alex, because he, he had relationship with the staff, with the custodians, with the nurses, and the doctors, and okay, you know.

02:08:21.000 --> 02:08:33.000
But they says, when Dr. Alexander first came, we, we used to talk amongst ourselves and we say, is he a brother? Or what?

02:08:33.000 --> 02:08:47.000
And then they figured it out, you know, that yes, yes, yes, he was. And, you know, in his heart above all, you know, and in his allegiances, and who he thought wasn't, you know, was important.

02:08:47.000 --> 02:08:57.000
Yeah. And that's the legacy of the family. And my other regret is that I didn't, I interviewed my aunt, I interviewed my brother, I interviewed my sister. This is after my father's death.

02:08:57.000 --> 02:09:08.000
And after my mother's death, and I interviewed some cousins, but I never interviewed my mother. And that was a big mistake.

02:09:08.000 --> 02:09:21.000
Because I think she was the solid rock behind that whole operation, holding that family together, going to a holiness church in Paris, California. She had to go too.

02:09:21.000 --> 02:09:27.000
You know, you know, with my uncle and aunt, and how did she do it?

02:09:27.000 --> 02:09:32.000
I like, yeah. Yeah. You can carry, you carried her with you though.

02:09:32.000 --> 02:09:39.000
Yeah. It's that quiet part, that, that, that's quite strange that she had. Yeah.

02:09:39.000 --> 02:09:48.000
Well, thank you so much. Thank you for everything you've done. And obviously, but also for spending time with us today, and telling this incredibly important story.

02:09:48.000 --> 02:09:54.000
Thank you. Yeah. Thank you. And I want to pick your brains about what to do with my, all my stuff.

02:09:54.000 --> 02:09:56.000
Okay. Yes. I got more.

02:09:56.000 --> 02:10:05.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

